Construction works for the 3B independent water project in Saudi Arabia have officially begun in the presence of significant officials like Khaled Z AlQureshi. Commissioned by the Saudi Water Partnership Company (SWPC), the project is projected to produce well about 570,000 m3 of potable water in a day, through the use of efficient technology. The 3B independent water project is located 65 kilometers north of the Dammam airport. The plant will supply water to the Qassim and Riyadh regions once it is commercially operational. When complete the plant will be maintained and operated by ENGIE. The construction works for the 3B independent water project officially began in the presence of the CEO of the Saudi Water Partnership Company, Khaled Z AlQureshi, representatives from the Nesma Company Limited, ENGIE – global energy company, alongside the Ajlan & Bros holding group. The plant will also include an impressive solar facility that gives 61 megawatts, which would be the largest in-house solar capability for a desalination plant in Saudi Arabia. This will contribute to helping the country to optimize the consumption of electricity as well as reduce grid reliance. Read Also US$ 48M+ Agreement Signed for Rixos Jeddah Resort Project Development in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia The construction works for the 3B independent water project are under the terms of a 25-year Water Purchase Agreement, and the plant’s construction will be financed by the consortium. Led by ENGIE, the consortium was awarded the project in 2021 after their submission of a bid with a tariff of SAR 1.591 per cubic meter of potable water to the Saudi Water Partnership Company. The project’s use of solar energy aligns directly with the country’s Vision 2030 and net-zero objectives. The initiatives aim to reduce Saudi Arabia’s dependency on fossil fuels while driving the shift to the use of cleaner energy.